  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do you do when you have no friends?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're feeling this way. It's tough to feel like you don't have friends, but there are steps you can take to build connections and improve your situation:\n\n1. **Engage in Activities You Enjoy**: Pursuing hobbies or interests can help you meet people with similar passions. Whether it's joining a sports team, taking a class, or participating in a club, shared activities provide a natural way to connect.\n\n2. **Volunteer**: Helping others can provide a sense of purpose and introduce you to compassionate, like-minded individuals. Volunteering for causes you care about can lead to meaningful friendships.\n\n3. **Reach Out to Acquaintances**: Sometimes, deepening existing casual relationships can turn acquaintances into friends. Invite someone for a coffee or suggest doing something together.\n\n4. **Attend Social Events**: Attend community events, workshops, or meetups related to your interests. These settings offer opportunities to strike up conversations and meet new people.\n\n5. **Work on Self-Confidence**: Building your self-esteem can make it easier to approach others and form connections. Practices like mindfulness, self-reflection, or speaking with a counselor can be beneficial.\n\n6. **Use Online Platforms**: Joining online communities or forums related to your interests can help you connect with others, especially if in-person interactions feel challenging.\n\n7. **Be Open and Patient**: Building friendships takes time. Be open to different types of people and give relationships the time they need to develop naturally.\n\n8. **Seek Professional Support**: If feelings of loneliness are overwhelming, consider reaching out to a mental health professional. They can provide strategies and support to help you navigate these feelings.\n\nRemember, you're not alone in feeling this way, and many people find themselves in similar situations at different points in their lives. Taking small, consistent steps can lead to meaningful connections over time.",
